<DESCRIPT>  OBITUARY; NAME; LIST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  FISHER, Maria, 87, founder of the Beethoven Society of America and the
Thelonious Monk Institute of Jazz; Thursday of brain cancer at her home in
Washington, D.C. Born in Wittenberg, Germany, Mrs. Fisher, whose family name
was Wollenweber, lived in England before moving to the United States in 1945.
She was an actress who appeared in more than 60 movies, and a soprano with the
London Opera Company and, under the name Maria de la Hull, with the Columbia
Opera Company in Washington.;    HAWKINS Sr., James Henry, 80, a grocer in Los
Angeles' Watts area who became an urban folk hero for standing up to local
gangs; Thursday of prostate cancer in Los Angeles. For years, gang members
threatened to chase the owner of Slater Market and his clan out of the
neighborhood, said his son, Elton Hawkins. They firebombed the Hawkins home,
fired up to 40 bullets into the house and attempted to ram it with a car.
Seventeen gang members were convicted of crimes against the Hawkins family.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DEATHS ELSEWHERE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Obituaries  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     McCALLION, James, 72, a character actor whose motion picture credits
include "North by Northwest" and "PT 109"; Thursday of kidney failure at
Valley Presbyterian Hospital in Van Nuys. Born in Londonderry, England, Mr.
McCallion first appeared on Broadway in 1927 at age 9 with Leon Errol in
"Yours Truly." Subsequent Broadway appearances in "Roosty" and "But for the
Grace of God" led to a film career with the Universal, RKO and Warner Bros.
studios. He portrayed Pappy McMahon, a badly burned sailor rescued by patrol
torpedo boat commander John F. Kennedy, in "PT 109," starring Cliff
Robertson.;    RAGNI, Gerome, 48, who co-wrote and starred in the racy
1960s-era musical "Hair"; Wednesday of cancer in New York City. Mr. Ragni,
along with James Rado, wrote the book and lyrics for the show that portrayed
the sexual liberation, anti-war movements and celebration of the flower
children of the 1960s. The musical was performed in 1967 at the New York
Shakespeare Festival. It was rewritten and emerged the next year on Broadway,
where it played 1,750 performances. The show, which featured profanity and
nudity, was revived in 1977 and made into a movie in 1979.;    REVELLE, Roger
R.D., 82, known as the father of the University of California, San Diego and a
pioneering researcher of global warming and other scientific theories; Monday
at a San Diego hospital after having suffered a heart attack last week. Mr.
Revelle was visiting his doctor Wednesday when his heart stopped during a
non-surgical cardiac exam, hospital officials said. Doctors resuscitated him
and admitted him to the intensive care unit, hospital spokeswoman Leslie Franz
said. One of UCSD's four colleges was named for Mr. Revelle in 1965, and he
had remained a professor emeritus there until his death. He was a former
director of the Scripps Institution of Oceanography, where he first made his
mark nationally as an oceanographer in the 1950s through research into the
warming of the Earth's climate, known as the "greenhouse effect.";   
SULLIVAN, Eleanor Regis, 62, editor and writer of mystery fiction who worked
under several pen names; Friday of cancer in New York City. Ms. Sullivan,
formerly of Cambridge, Mass., compiled and edited more than two dozen
anthologies of mystery and suspense fiction. She had been editor in chief of
Ellery Queen's Mystery Magazine since 1982. Ms. Sullivan also wrote fiction
and non-fiction that appeared in a variety of books, magazines and newspapers,
and has been reprinted in several languages. Her fiction often appeared under
the pen names Lika Ness, Julia DeHahn and Ruth Graviros.  </TEXT>
